metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 1 #150
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ 0.1, ____ 0.2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

metadata.name: KONSTRUKTS #153
metadata.description:
A study of building and destroying. I built this. You may knock it over.

Humans are both creators and destroyers. One of the earliest games children learn to play is building with blocks, then knocking them down. This simple activity is teaching kids about gravity, cause and effect, and imposing their will on the world around them. As children grow older, the gap between these opposing actions widens. The intention behind knocking things down becomes less innocent, and creators aren't as excited to see their work destroyed.

In 1915, the Russian avant-garde founded the abstract art movement known as Constructivism, rejecting everything except for the absolute purest aspects of form and material. This art was used in service of the Russian revolution and utilized heavily in its propaganda, intended to highlight the utilitarian nature of industrial progress. Mainly, building the new Russia. Its influence is lasting, and can be seen throughout art and design trends even today.

When Russia invaded Ukraine in February of 2022, footage of missiles and airstrikes decimating Ukrainian buildings permeated the media. Ukrainian lives, kitchens, windowsill gardens, and family photos tumbled to the ground. Like children's blocks. Things that took a lifetime to build were destroyed in seconds. 

KONSTRUKTS represents this duality in creation and destruction. Stacked children's blocks are rendered in the style of Constructivist designs like El Lissitzky's Proun series, and Alexander Rodchenko's posters. With a simple tap, blocks (or buildings) can be knocked to the ground.

- Tap anywhere to reveal the KONSTRUKTS menu in the top left. Tap the menu for several options.
- KONSTRUKTS can be exported as USDZ or GLTF models to be used in augmented reality or the metaverse.
- Export a full resolution PNG image from the menu.
- If you knocked over the blocks, you can reset them from the menu.

KONSTRUKTS is built entirely with code, using Three.js, JavaScript, and GLSL.

metadata.name: Impressions of Order #272
metadata.description:
‚ÄòImpressions of Order‚Äô is a collection of 300 generative compositions. 

Inspired by 90s ROM cartridges, server farms and future cityscapes this project explores perception and documentation of ‚Äòorder‚Äô within complex systems. 

--------------------------------------------------------

This artwork is best enjoyed in high-resolution so that the subtle layering, colour shifts, variation in hard and soft edges, faint impressions of construction, and the various low-probability glitchy events can be fully appreciated. 

By default, the artwork will load in 2K resolution (1400 x 2000 px). It is recommended that you view the work in 4K or 6K to appreciate the finer details. 

The keyboard buttons: ‚Äú2‚Äù, ‚Äú4‚Äù, and ‚Äú6‚Äù can be pressed to change the resolution to 2K, 4K and 6K resolution accordingly. 

To download an image at its current resolution, press the keyboard button ‚ÄúS‚Äù.

metadata.name: Abstract Memories #157
metadata.description:
I try to explore the unknown nature of objects in an emotional abstraction. Instead of imposing an entirely personal feeling on the canvas, I draw something out of the canvas with the tools of expressive abstraction and color contrast. The content of an abstract painting completely bypasses all those mental filters. Abstract painting is the revelation of the inner life of the human soul; it transforms from words to visual identity. The abstract painting speaks the language of the imaginary world, a language that struggles with complexities.
I have always been interested in laying out patterns on the flat surface of the canvas and deciding how to cut and relate the frame to those elements on my design page. This focus is created through the influence of unpredictable handprints, batik prints, watercolors, and other oriental objects in my works. The desire for this decorative approach led me to cut the three-dimensional environment into a repeating flat pattern so that the rhythm of the shapes emphasizes the strong structure. Also, my attempt to use contrasting colors right next to each other - warm reds and oranges against great neutral greens, blues, and grays - is influenced by the challenging thinking of color and the lightness of impressionism in my work, where pure colors "in a reflection in mind And the contrast makes them even more vivid. They are precisely like the works we enjoy in the real world of reflected light. They can be easily overlooked in the dull colors of a canvas or on a productive work page; these contrasts and complementary color silences side by side. , create a magnificent symphony of colors.
I try to explore the unknown nature of objects in an emotional abstraction. Instead of imposing an entirely personal feeling on the canvas, I draw something out of the canvas with the tools of expressive abstraction and color contrast. The content of an abstract painting completely bypasses all those mental filters. Abstract painting is the revelation of the inner life of the human soul; it transforms from words to visual identity. The abstract painting speaks the language of the imaginary world, a language that struggles with complexities.
These types of art provide humanity with a background voice that profoundly soothes and heals our souls precisely because it is not figurative and, therefore, malleable and defined visually. An abstract painter seeks to depict the world around us in a way that is not what we see, but the message is that "this is what the world feels like." An abstract work puts the viewer in a position to create an interactive experience with the art by giving them the freedom to say, "this is for me."Looking at this work, we see pieces of colors and shapes you might imagine in a moment Gustav Klimt's Kiss, Ren√© Magritte's Golconde, etc. The ability of abstraction goes through the history of art and the human mind and remembers each one with hints.

To spread the vibe of my beautiful community, minters will own 50% of the royalty on each secondary sale.
Twenty-two different color palettes and three different borders with random colors are used in this artwork.
Made in p5js
Created September 2022
Artist: @ChistaAi
